The <b>Tuxtla Quail-Dove</b> (<i>Geotrygon carrikeri</i>) or <b>Veracruz Quail-Dove</b> is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Columbidae" title="Columbidae">Columbidae</a> family. It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to pristine <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane" title="Montane" class="mw-redirect">montane</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rainforest" title="Rainforest">rainforest</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierra_de_los_Tuxtlas" title="Sierra de los Tuxtlas">Sierra de los Tuxtlas</a> of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>'s <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veracruz" title="Veracruz">Veracruz</a> state. It was once considered a subspecies of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purplish-backed_Quail-Dove" title="Purplish-backed Quail-Dove">Purplish-backed Quail-Dove</a> of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_America" title="Central America">Central America</a>.
Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are lowland and montane <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tropical_and_subtropical_moist_broadleaf_forests" title="Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests">tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests</a>. It is threatened by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat_loss" title="Habitat loss" class="mw-redirect">habitat loss</a>.
